data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` tree **won't compile** because the overload now expects `Func<…>`, not `Expression<Func<…>>`.

**Fix** — replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression-tree construction needed anymore.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Sibling complex types now get uniquified columns.**
`ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared a `Street` column. EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street1`) to disambiguate.

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.**
`Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix** — if you have an existing database, pin the old names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old (short) name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

Or generate a migration and let EF rename the columns in the DB.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. This carries the **redacted** SQL for logging (inlined constants scrubbed unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on).

**Fix:**

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)        // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText (redacted) for logging,
        // command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface — they all gained the same parameter.
